00:27:13.841 --> 00:27:16.720
to make those corrections.

616
00:27:18.840 --> 00:27:22.969
Landmark Accessibility:
What are website landmarks? 

617
00:27:22.969 --> 00:27:25.593
They help screen readers 
identify sections of the website.

618
00:27:25.593 --> 00:27:29.708
Identifies areas like 
navigation, main content areas, 

619
00:27:29.708 --> 00:27:32.840
sidebars, search bar, 
footer, and copyright.

620
00:27:32.840 --> 00:27:36.853
On Unilever, they didn't
really have those. 

621
00:27:36.853 --> 00:27:38.140
They have those 
sections identified 

622
00:27:38.140 --> 00:27:40.960
and I can show you that 
in a minute as well, but,

623
00:27:40.960 --> 00:27:45.520
you use these landmarks, 
or use ARIA labels,

624
00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:50.399
to help identify if HTML
is falling short for you.

625
00:27:50.399 --> 00:27:52.665
It's a good idea to have
labels everywhere if possible 

626
00:27:52.665 --> 00:27:57.049
but know that HTML5 has 
a lot of this structure built-in. 

627
00:27:57.049 --> 00:28:00.409
Not all screen readers 
use ARIA label as its 

628
00:28:00.409 --> 00:28:03.440
main source of information
but it's definitely still good

629
00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:07.360
to consider adding 
these labels in.

630
00:28:08.960 --> 00:28:10.207
Heading Accessibility: 

631
00:28:10.207 --> 00:28:12.789
Think of each page as 
an outline for a paper, 

632
00:28:12.789 --> 00:28:15.553
starting with H1 as a title 
at the top of the page 

633
00:28:15.553 --> 00:28:16.789
then continue H2, H3, H4. 

634
00:28:16.789 --> 00:28:20.226
Use headings to convey 
meaning and structure. 

635
00:28:20.226 --> 00:28:22.640
When I'm working 
with copywriters,

636
00:28:22.640 --> 00:28:26.349
I definitely try to guide this
as much as possible 

637
00:28:26.349 --> 00:28:28.744
when I'm working with them, 
trying to help me 

638
00:28:28.744 --> 00:28:31.135
convey meaning to everything, 
including images. 

639
00:28:31.135 --> 00:28:35.360
I bring them into the conversation 
across the board.

640
00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:39.128
Think about, now that 
you have the copy 

641
00:28:39.128 --> 00:28:41.062
and you've got the images going, 
think about the design 

642
00:28:41.062 --> 00:28:43.410
and the page structure. 
This can help someone 

643
00:28:43.410 --> 00:28:44.908
when navigating the website. 

644
00:28:44.908 --> 00:28:47.221
You can see here 
proper white space 

645
00:28:47.221 --> 00:28:49.254
makes a relationship between 
the content more apparent. 

646
00:28:49.254 --> 00:28:52.466
Style headings to group content, 
reduce clutter, and make it easier 

647
00:28:52.466 --> 00:28:53.967
to scan and understand. 

648
00:28:53.967 --> 00:28:57.369
The example on the left 
has the main heading 

649
00:28:57.369 --> 00:28:59.062
and the subheading 
grouped together. 

650
00:28:59.062 --> 00:29:01.272
The image is thrown in there. 
You don't know what 

651
00:29:01.272 --> 00:29:04.045
the association is with. 
In the example on the right, 

652
00:29:04.045 --> 00:29:06.266
the main heading and the image 
are grouped together 

653
00:29:06.266 --> 00:29:09.006
and then the subheadings
are in their own area 

654
00:29:09.006 --> 00:29:13.840
and the structure
makes a lot more sense.

655
00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.246
Notes on Reading: 
When reading on the screen, 

656
00:29:18.246 --> 00:29:21.117
users benefit from having text 
at a lower reading level. 

657
00:29:21.117 --> 00:29:23.144
While it's not required 
for accessibility, 

658
00:29:23.144 --> 00:29:25.334
it's best to write at 
as low a reading level 

659
00:29:25.334 --> 00:29:26.674
is appropriate 
for your content. 

660
00:29:26.674 --> 00:29:28.728
Doing so benefits people 
with cognitive impairments, 

661
00:29:28.728 --> 00:29:31.506
people who do not speak 
English as the first language, 

662
00:29:31.506 --> 00:29:34.740
and people who may be 
distracted while reading. 

663
00:29:34.740 --> 00:29:37.401
Some of the best practices
for readability include 

664
00:29:37.401 --> 00:29:41.283
writing at a high school grade level 
where possible and appropriate.

665
00:29:41.283 --> 00:29:44.749
Limit paragraphs to around 
80 words, if possible. 

666
00:29:44.749 --> 00:29:48.080
Avoid jargon and difficult language, 
when possible.

667
00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:50.853
One of the tips I have is 
use an authoring tool 

668
00:29:50.853 --> 00:29:52.240
such as Hemingway Editor.

669
00:29:52.240 --> 00:29:54.219
It's a decent tool.
You can get in there 

670
00:29:54.219 --> 00:29:56.279
and see what 
your readability is. 

671
00:29:56.279 --> 00:29:59.042
I wouldn't overthink this. 
I know it really depends on 

672
00:29:59.042 --> 00:30:01.558
the content of the website 
and if you have a very 

673
00:30:01.558 --> 00:30:04.715
scientific website you have to 
write at a certain level, but, 

674
00:30:04.715 --> 00:30:09.840
if you don't need to make
it over-complicated, don't.

675
00:30:10.240 --> 00:30:12.556
Link and Button Accessibility: 

676
00:30:12.556 --> 00:30:17.320
The example on the left 
shows no information. 

677
00:30:17.320 --> 00:30:19.200
You see this on a lot of websites: 
LEARN MORE.

678
00:30:19.200 --> 00:30:21.717
In some cases 
you can't help it, 

679
00:30:21.717 --> 00:30:23.279
like on a blog roll 
you see "LEARN MORE" a lot

680
00:30:23.279 --> 00:30:25.217
but it doesn't provide
enough information 

681
00:30:25.217 --> 00:30:27.954
for screen readers or people 
with visual impairments, 

682
00:30:27.954 --> 00:30:29.742
kind of what that means... 

683
00:30:29.742 --> 00:30:33.146
compared to the button on the right. 
It says: See All Events. 

684
00:30:33.146 --> 00:30:35.064
You know directly where that's 
